Cyclistic Bike-Share
Data-Backed Recommendations
 

Prepared by: Michael Asamoah
Date: June 2026
Dataset: Cyclistic Trip Data — December 2025 to January 2026
Records Analysed: 124,475 cleaned trip records
Business Task: How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

Summary of Key Findings
The following findings from the analysis inform the three recommendations below.

Finding	Key Insight
Ride Frequency	Members account for 82.61% of all rides — casual riders only 17.39%
Ride Length	Casual riders take longer trips on average — 12.99 mins vs 11.19 mins for members
Day of Week	Members ride consistently all week — casual riders take longest rides on weekends
Bike Type	Casual riders prefer electric bikes more strongly — 73.10% vs 63.10% for members
Time of Day	Members show commuter peaks at 8AM and 5PM — casual riders peak gradually in the afternoon

 









Recommendation 1
Title
Introduce a "Weekend Warrior" Membership Tier
Data Insight
Members account for 82.61% of rides — casual riders only 17.39%
Recommended Action	
Launch a discounted weekend-only membership targeting casual riders who log more than 3 rides a month. This creates a low-friction entry point, steadily converting frequent casual users into recurring subscription revenue.

Recommendation 2

Title	
Target Leisure Locations
Data Insight	
Casual riders peak in the afternoon and ride longest on weekends
Recommended Action	
Focus marketing campaigns and on-the-ground promotions directly at recreational parks, tourist spots, and waterfront leisure areas. Targeting them at the exact moment they are looking for leisure activities will yield a much higher conversion rate.

Recommendation 3

Title	
Electric Bike Membership Incentive
Data Insight	
 Casual riders prefer electric bikes 73.10% of the time
Recommended Action	
Position the Cyclistic membership not just as a ride-share, but as a superior alternative to e-bike ownership. Emphasize the benefits of a premium, fully maintained fleet without the heavy upfront costs, storage issues, or maintenance fees of owning a personal electric bike.

 
Limitations & Notes
•	Dataset covers only December 2025 and January 2026 — findings reflect winter riding behaviour and may not represent year-round patterns.
•	24,553 rows with missing station names were removed — this may slightly underrepresent electric bike usage.
•	Personally identifiable information was removed — rider-level tracking across trips is not possible.

